  <subsection>
    <title>Functions</title>
    <p>
      A function input something and output something. Some people say functions eat in something and spit out something. The function given by <m> f (x) = x^2 </m> takes in a number <m>x</m> and gives out <m>x^2</m>. When fed <m>y</m> it yields <m>y^2</m>, when fed <m>7</m> it yields <m>49</m>, and when fed ðŸ¤¦ it yields <m>\text{ðŸ¤¦}^2</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Even if we write <q>the function <m> f (x) = x^2 </m> </q> so often, the function is really <m>f</m> instead of <m> f (x) </m>: the little tail <m>(x)</m> is only an attempt to name the input, and technically <em><m> f (x) </m> is a number</em>. I can change it to whatever, like <q>the function <m>f</m> defined by <m> f (\cdot) = (\cdot)^2 </m></q>. A fancier way to write a function is <m> f : x \mapsto x^2 </m> where the barred arrow reads <q>maps to</q>. It literally expresses the same function as <m> y \mapsto y^2 </m>. Earlier people wrote <q>the function <m> y = x^2 </m></q>: it's really because in old times <m>x</m> is the default name for input and <m>y</m> for output. It was useful, especially if you didn't have a thousand symbols to keep track of as we have today ðŸ¤¦.
    </p>
    <p>
      Functions have input and output types. I don't want to know what's <m> \sin \text{ðŸ¥‘} </m> unless I intend to mean a number by ðŸ¥‘. A function <m> f : \mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}^m </m> inputs an <m>n</m>-vector and outputs an <m>m</m>-vector, with the unbarred arrow reading <q>to</q>. Input and output types together determine the function type, like the function given by <m> f (x) = x^2 </m> has type <m> \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R} </m>.
    </p>
    <reading-questions>
      <title>Questions</title>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>f</m> is given by <m> f ( x, y ) = x^2 + y </m>, what's <m> f ( x, z ) </m>, <m> f ( y, x ) </m>, <m> f ( x, x ) </m>, and <m> f ( \text{ðŸŸ }, \text{ðŸŸ¦} ) </m>? How is it different from the function <m> g : u, v \mapsto u^2 + v </m>, the function <m> h : u, v \mapsto v^2 + u </m>, and the function given by <m> F ( \ast, \circ ) = \ast + \circ^2 </m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What are the type constraints so that we can chain two functions <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>: we first apply <m>f</m> on the input to get an intermediate result, and then apply <m>g</m> on the intermediate result to get the eventual output? What's the type <m> \ldots \to \ldots </m> of the composite function? How to define the composite function <m> \ldots \mapsto \ldots </m>? Why the composite function is written as <m> g \circ f </m> instead of <m> f \circ g </m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain in your own words how <q>left-multiplying by <m>\mathbf{A}</m></q> is a function from vectors to vectors once given a matrix <m>\mathbf{A}</m>. If <m>\mathbf{A}</m> is an (<m>m</m><times/><m>n</m>)-matrix, what's the type of the function?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Given a function <m> f : \mathbb{R}^2 \to \mathbb{R}^n </m>, how can we construct a function <m> x, y \mapsto f ( y, x ) </m> by composing <m>f</m> with some very special function? In other words, how to express <m> h : u, v \mapsto v^2 + u </m> as a composite function part of which is <m> g : u, v \mapsto u^2 + v </m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Given (for <m>P</m> and <m> Q : \mathbb{R}^2 \to \mathbb{R} </m>)
            <me>
              \int_{ \partial \Omega } \left( P \mathop{\mathrm{d}\!} x + Q \mathop{\mathrm{d}\!} y \right) = \iint_{\Omega} \left( -\frac{ \mathop{\partial\!} P }{ \mathop{\partial\!} y } + \frac{ \mathop{\partial\!} Q }{ \mathop{\partial\!} x } \right) \mathop{\mathrm{d}\!} x \mathop{\mathrm{d}\!} y
            </me>,
            obtain
            <me>
              \int_{ \partial \Omega } \left( P \mathop{\mathrm{d}\!} y - Q \mathop{\mathrm{d}\!} x \right) = \iint_{\Omega} \left( \frac{ \mathop{\partial\!} P }{ \mathop{\partial\!} x } + \frac{ \mathop{\partial\!} Q }{ \mathop{\partial\!} y }\right) \mathop{\mathrm{d}\!} x \mathop{\mathrm{d}\!} y
            </me>.
            You don't need any calculus to do this. Not at all. Absolutely zero.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </reading-questions>
